<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1916-09-27T11:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1916-09-27T11:00:00-05:00" n="762" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d762">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 300.115/10089</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Great Britain</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_LIB1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Laughlin</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-09-27T17:00:00+01:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">September 27, 1916, 5 p. m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 3.20 p. m.</hi>]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>4947. Your 3844, September 18, 4 p. m. Reply of Foreign Office to
                                representations transmitted by despatch 4706. In reply to oral
                                representations Foreign Office unofficially informs that British
                                Government not willing to grant facilities for any needles of German
                                origin since needles can mostly be procured from United Kingdom.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="#p_LIB1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Laughlin</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>